Virind <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#99CC66><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bthepunchingbag74708.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=publius>Publius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Martial, Baby, MARTIAL.</span><br>  Posts: 472<br> <font color=#660000>(4/5/02 3:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub83.ezboard.com/fthepunchingbag74708frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1851.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> In spite of, uhh, the events described in my post above. In spite of the fact that I still haven't managed to get over it, or reconcile myself to it, or even get on with my life in any meaningful way in the last two and a half years, in spite of ALL that, I still have to agree with Virind.<br>
<br>
A person's life is his or her own, to do with as they please. If they choose to end it, they have that right.<br>
<br>
You can't just pay lip service to the concept of human rights and ignore this aspect of it. We all have the right to die. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/umingz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mingz</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Martial, Baby, MARTIAL.</span><br>  Posts: 582<br> <font color=#660000>(4/5/02 8:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub83.ezboard.com/fthepunchingbag74708frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1851.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> Yep I agree with Pub on that point. (note, while im thinking of it: this thread needs to go into the misc category I'd say.)  I agree with the idea, but at the same time I disagree with suicide completely based on depression. Like I said, life isn't always pleasant, but I feel strongly that it can be enjoyable. I've been there emotionally, and have seen all of the people in my life that I call friends and loved one's go through their fair share of pain as well. I would go as far as to say I've saved a few people from suicidel. Self termination based on depression is a state of mind. It's a self-esteem implosion. It feeds upon itself. I consider it a disease, and cureable. If a person has lapsed into this state, I can only treat it as such, and try to repair them. It's their right to do it. It's my right to help them find an alternative.<br>
<br>
On a sidenote nature can be cruel. Not all organisms are fit to survive. This is the harsh reality we are given. This awareness keeps me strong when the pain borders on unbearible. I don't want to give in. I want to beat back the things that would kill me. I see life as a struggle, not a walk in the park gone awry. Civilization separates us so far from this reality, that I feel many are depressed simply because they have no awareness of this. It's like they see the world as lacking where it should be more instead of being greatful for what they have. They don't want to be burdened with choices. They don't even want to think. They just want it to stop. Every little pitfall is  like being in a deep hole, tied up, unable to move and suffocating once in this state. That's why I feel while it is their right to die, but it is also my obligation as their fellow human to help them out. Those who do make it out are often not only able to deal and be as happy as the next guy, but are sometimes even stronger for it. Not always. It's not a  Disney story where after the evil spell is broken they're fine, but I've seen it happen.  That's not selfish. That's helping a person become a fighter. That's an advanced stage of evolution if you ask me. <br>
<br>
 Life isn't a given. Finding even a semi-harmonious relationship with all of life's choices and ups and downs is not given. It requires maintenance. We do this maintenance through art, friendship, creativity, imagination, and exertion both mental and physical. We develop self-discipline. We develop tolerances. We maintain some level of hygene. We maintain some level of social position, within various heirarchies from friends, to games, to communities, to the economy...to where-ever others are concerned. We study. We eat the right foods. We wack off. We do whatever it is we need to do to live. We find whatever rythm.  It isn't however a gimme.<br>
<br>
As was said there are a zillion people and one less is more air for the rest of us. I'm fully fine with executing those who would shit in the worlds easter basket, and I'm also fine with those people offing themselves. It's those who are simply confused and miserable that I commiserate with, and will assist in surving. It's especially sad when kids kill themselves, but horrible when any once functional person falls into the aformentioned downward spiral. I don't think it's selfish necessarily to want them to be around, unless of course we're talking about forcing them to stay alive without offering them real help. Here johnny we're going to put you in this protective bubble, but not going to help beyond that. <br>
<br>
Sorry about the long post. Well, no I'm not. hehe. If you read it and didn't enjoy it, that was your choice. The key to helping yourself or someone out of suicidal straits is restoring one solid belief in them. There is one belief at the core of everyone, or so I believe. From this stem all other beliefs in a complicated matrix. Think of them as dots connected by lines, forming a web. If one fails, other that are attached cave in. This leads to confusion, frustration, and depression sometimes, and at other times exulatation.<br>
<br>
